10 SERVICES AND PERSONNEL OF:
11 (I) THE OFFICE OF THE ATTORNEY GENERAL;
12 (II) THE DEPARTMENT OF STATE POLICE; AND
13 (III) OTHER STATE AND LAW ENFORCEMENT UNITS.
14 (2) THE UNITS LISTED IN PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION
15 SHALL COOPERATE, TO THE EXTENT PRACTICABLE, WITH THE OMBUDSMAN AND
16 THE OMBUDSMAN’S STAFF.
17 (D) IN COOPERATION WITH THE SECRETARY OF BUDGET AND
18 MANAGEMENT, THE ATTORNEY GENERAL SHALL SET MINIMUM SALARIES,
19 QUALIFICATIONS, AND STANDARDS OF TRAINING AND EXPERIENCE FOR POSITIONS
20 IN THE OFFICE.
21 6–5A–05.
22 (A) THE BUDGET OF THE OMBUDSMAN AND THE OFFICE SHALL BE A PART
23 OF THE BUDGET OF THE OFFICE OF THE ATTORNEY GENERAL.
24 (B) SALARIES OF THE OMBUDSMAN AND ASSISTANT OMBUDSMEN AND
25 EXPENSES FOR RENT, EQUIPMENT, SUPPLIES, AND GENERAL OPERATING EXPENSES
26 NECESSARY FOR THE WORK OF THE OFFICE SHALL BE AS PROVIDED IN THE STATE
27 BUDGET.
28 (C) THE GOVERNOR SHALL PROVIDE IN THE STATE BUDGET SUFFICIENT
29 MONEY FOR THE OFFICE TO HIRE NECESSARY STAFF.

HOUSE BILL 980 17
1 (D) IF THE BUDGET FOR THE OFFICE IS INSUFFICIENT TO ALLOW THE
2 OFFICE TO PERFORM THE DUTIES OF THE OFFICE, THE OMBUDSMAN MAY APPLY TO
3 THE BOARD OF PUBLIC WORKS FOR ADDITIONAL MONEY FROM THE GENERAL
4 EMERGENCY FUND.
5 6–5A–06.
6 (A) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION, OR AS
7 OTHERWISE PROVIDED BY LAW, ALL PERSONNEL OF THE OFFICE ARE SUBJECT TO
8 THE PROVISIONS OF THE STATE PERSONNEL AND PENSIONS ARTICLE.
9 (B) THE COMPENSATION OF THE FOLLOWING PERSONNEL SHALL BE
10 DETERMINED BY THE OMBUDSMAN AND, IF POSSIBLE, IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE
11 STATE PAY PLAN:
12 (1) ASSISTANT OMBUDSMEN;
13 (2) ATTORNEYS THAT ARE SPECIAL APPOINTEES OR IN THE
14 MANAGEMENT SERVICE; AND
15 (3) ALL POSITIONS IN MANAGEMENT, PROFESSIONAL, AND SKILLED
16 SERVICE CLASSIFICATIONS UNIQUE TO THE OFFICE.
17 (C) (1) AT LEAST 45 DAYS BEFORE THE EFFECTIVE DATE OF A CHANGE IN
18 SALARY PLAN, THE OMBUDSMAN SHALL SUBMIT TO THE SECRETARY OF BUDGET
19 AND MANAGEMENT EACH CHANGE THAT INVOLVES AN INCREASE OR A DECREASE IN
20 SALARY RANGES OTHER THAN THOSE ASSOCIATED WITH ROUTINE CLASSIFICATIONS
21 AND PROMOTIONS OR GENERAL SALARY INCREASES APPROVED BY THE GENERAL
22 ASSEMBLY.
23 (2) THE SECRETARY OF BUDGET AND MANAGEMENT SHALL:
24 (I) REVIEW THE PROPOSED CHANGES; AND
25 (II) AT LEAST 15 DAYS BEFORE THE EFFECTIVE DATE OF THE
26 PROPOSED CHANGES, ADVISE THE OMBUDSMAN WHETHER THE CHANGES WOULD
27 HAVE AN ADVERSE EFFECT ON COMPARABLE STATE JOBS.
28 (3) FAILURE OF THE SECRETARY TO RESPOND IN A TIMELY MANNER
29 MAY NOT BE CONSIDERED A STATEMENT OF ADVERSE EFFECT UNDER PARAGRAPH
30 (2)(II) OF THIS SUBSECTION.

18 HOUSE BILL 980
1 (D) ON OR BEFORE JANUARY 31 EACH YEAR, BEGINNING IN 2028, THE
2 OMBUDSMAN SHALL REPORT TO THE SECRETARY OF BUDGET AND MANAGEMENT
3 AND, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THIS ARTICLE, TO THE GENERAL
4 ASSEMBLY ALL PERSONNEL POSITIONS, CLASSIFICATIONS, AND SALARIES IN THE
5 OFFICE AS OF THE END OF THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING CALENDAR YEAR.
6 6–5A–07.
7 THE OFFICE SHALL:
8 (1) IDENTIFY, RECEIVE, INVESTIGATE, AND SEEK THE RESOLUTION
9 OR REFERRAL OF COMPLAINTS MADE BY OR ON BEHALF OF A CHILD INVOLVED IN
10 CHILD IN NEED OF ASSISTANCE CASES CONCERNING ANY ACT, OMISSION, PRACTICE,
11 POLICY, OR PROCEDURE OF A STATE OR LOCAL AGENCY OR ANY PERSON WORKING
12 ON BEHALF OF THE AGENCY THAT MAY ADVERSELY AFFECT THE HEALTH, SAFETY,
13 OR WELFARE OF THE CHILD;
14 (2) INSPECT AND REVIEW THE OPERATION, POLICIES, AND
15 PROCEDURES OF FOSTER CARE HOMES, GROUP HOMES, KINSHIP CARE HOMES,
16 RESIDENTIAL TREATMENT FACILITIES, SHELTERS FOR THE CARE OF ABUSED OR
17 NEGLECTED CHILDREN, AND INDEPENDENT LIVING ARRANGEMENTS OPERATED,
18 LICENSED, OR APPROVED FOR PAYMENT BY THE DEPARTMENT OR A LOCAL
19 DEPARTMENT OR USED BY THE DEPARTMENT OR BY A LOCAL DEPARTMENT FOR THE
20 CARE OF CHILDREN IN ITS CUSTODY;
21 (3) REVIEW, EVALUATE, REPORT, AND MAKE RECOMMENDATIONS TO
22 A STATE OR LOCAL AGENCY CONCERNING PROCEDURES ESTABLISHED BY THE
23 AGENCY TO PROVIDE SERVICES TO CHILDREN AND FAMILIES THAT ARE AT RISK OF
24 ABUSE OR NEGLECT, CHILDREN IN STATE OR INSTITUTIONAL CUSTODY, OR
25 CHILDREN AND FAMILIES WHO RECEIVE CHILD PROTECTIVE KINSHIP CARE OR
26 FOSTER CARE SERVICES;
27 (4) RECEIVE, INVESTIGATE, AND MAKE REFERRALS TO OTHER STATE
28 OR LOCAL AGENCIES, OR TAKE OTHER APPROPRIATE ACTIONS WITH RESPECT TO A
29 COMPLAINT RECEIVED BY THE OFFICE REGARDING THE ACTIONS OF THE
30 DEPARTMENT OR A LOCAL DEPARTMENT OR A STATE–FUNDED PRIVATE ENTITY
31 THAT PROVIDES SERVICES TO CHILDREN AND FAMILIES WHO ARE AT RISK OF ABUSE
32 OR NEGLECT, CHILDREN IN STATE OR INSTITUTIONAL CUSTODY, OR CHILDREN AND
33 FAMILIES WHO RECEIVE CHILD PROTECTIVE, KINSHIP CARE, OR FOSTER CARE
34 SERVICES;
35 (5) ESTABLISH AND MAINTAIN A 24–HOUR TOLL–FREE TELEPHONE
36 HELPLINE AND WEBSITE TO RECEIVE AND RESPOND TO CALLS FROM INDIVIDUALS

HOUSE BILL 980 19
1 REGARDING THE WELFARE OF CHILDREN UNDER THE JURISDICTION OF THE
2 DEPARTMENT OR A LOCAL DEPARTMENT;
3 (6) CONDUCT UNANNOUNCED SITE VISITS AT REASONABLE TIMES
4 AND IN A REASONABLE MANNER TO ANY INSTITUTION OR FACILITY TO WHICH
5 CHILDREN ARE COMMITTED OR PLACED, IF:
6 (I) THE OMBUDSMAN, BEFORE CONDUCTING AN
7 UNANNOUNCED SITE VISIT, HAS INITIATED AN INVESTIGATION INTO THE RESPONSE
8 OR DISPOSITION OF AN ALLEGATION OF ABUSE OR NEGLECT AT THE INSTITUTION
9 OR FACILITY; AND
10 (II) THERE IS A REASONABLE BASIS TO BELIEVE THAT AN
11 UNANNOUNCED SITE VISIT IS NECESSARY TO CARRY OUT THE OMBUDSMAN’S
12 RESPONSIBILITIES UNDER THIS SUBTITLE;
13 (7) CONSULT WITH ANY APPROPRIATE STATE OR COUNTY AGENCY OR
14 STATE–FUNDED PRIVATE ENTITY PROVIDING CHILD WELFARE SERVICES TO
15 CHILDREN, AND MAY REQUEST FROM ANY SUCH ENTITY, WHICH IS HEREBY
16 AUTHORIZED AND DIRECTED TO PROVIDE, SUCH COOPERATION AND ASSISTANCE AS
17 WILL ENABLE THE CHILD ADVOCATE TO PROPERLY PERFORM ITS RESPONSIBILITIES
18 UNDER THIS SECTION; AND
19 (8) ESTABLISH AND IMPLEMENT PROCEDURES FOR RECEIVING,
20 PROCESSING, RESPONDING TO, AND RESOLVING COMPLAINTS MADE BY OR ON
21 BEHALF OF CHILDREN WHO ARE RECIPIENTS OF THE SERVICES OF THE LOCAL
22 DEPARTMENTS, AS PROVIDED FOR IN § 6–5A–09 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
23 6–5A–08.
24 (A) THE OMBUDSMAN MAY:
25 (1) REVIEW AND COPY RELEVANT LAWS, POLICIES, PROCEDURES,
26 AND DEPARTMENT AND LOCAL DEPARTMENT RECORDS AND REPORTS, INCLUDING
27 RECORDS RELATING TO AN INDIVIDUAL CHILD;
28 (2) CONDUCT INTERVIEWS WITH STAFF, CHILDREN, AND OTHERS;
29 (3) ISSUE SUBPOENAS TO COMPEL THE ATTENDANCE AND TESTIMONY
30 OF WITNESSES OR THE PRODUCTION OF BOOKS, PAPERS, AND OTHER DOCUMENTS;
31 (4) ADMINISTER OATHS TO WITNESSES IN ANY MATTER UNDER
32 INVESTIGATION IN THE OFFICE; AND

20 HOUSE BILL 980
1 (5) IF THE OMBUDSMAN CONSIDERS THAT LEGISLATION WOULD
2 AFFECT THE INTERESTS OF PERSONS UNDER ITS JURISDICTION, RECOMMEND THE
3 LEGISLATION TO THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY.
4 (B) (1) IF A PERSON TO WHOM A SUBPOENA IS ISSUED UNDER
5 SUBSECTION (A)(3) OF THIS SECTION FAILS TO APPEAR OR, HAVING APPEARED,
6 REFUSES TO GIVE TESTIMONY, OR FAILS TO PRODUCE THE BOOKS, PAPERS, OR
7 OTHER DOCUMENTS REQUIRED, THE OMBUDSMAN MAY APPLY TO THE
8 APPROPRIATE CIRCUIT COURT FOR RELIEF.
9 (2) THE APPROPRIATE COURT MAY ORDER THE PERSON TO APPEAR
10 AND GIVE TESTIMONY OR PRODUCE THE BOOKS, PAPERS, OR OTHER DOCUMENTS,
11 AS APPLICABLE.
12 6–5A–09.
13 (A) A CHILD WHO IS A RECIPIENT OF THE SERVICES OF THE DEPARTMENT
14 OR A LOCAL DEPARTMENT OR A CHILD IDENTIFIED AS A CHILD IN NEED OF
15 ASSISTANCE UNDER TITLE 3, SUBTITLE 8 OF THE COURTS ARTICLE MAY FILE A
16 COMPLAINT WITH THE OMBUDSMAN:
17 (1) BY CALLING THE OMBUDSMAN’S 24–HOUR TOLL–FREE HELPLINE;
18 (2) BY FILING THE COMPLAINT ELECTRONICALLY WITH THE OFFICE;
19 (3) BY MEETING IN PERSON WITH STAFF FROM THE OFFICE;
20 (4) THROUGH AN ADULT REPRESENTING THE CHILD’S INTERESTS; OR
21 (5) BY ANY OTHER REASONABLE MEANS ESTABLISHED BY THE
22 OMBUDSMAN.
23 (B) THE COMPLAINT PROCESS SHALL BE CONFIDENTIAL, EXPEDIENT, AND
24 RESPONSIVE TO THE CHILD’S PERCEPTION OF SAFETY ISSUES AND THE CHILD’S
25 EMOTIONAL NEEDS.
26 (C) THE OMBUDSMAN SHALL ESTABLISH AND IMPLEMENT APPROPRIATE
27 RESPONSE TIMES AND SAFETY MEASURES FOR DIFFERENT TYPES OF COMPLAINTS.
28 (D) FOR A CHILD WITH SAFETY CONCERNS ABOUT THE CHILD’S
29 OUT–OF–HOME PLACEMENT, THE CHILD’S SAFETY MUST BE PARAMOUNT SO THAT

HOUSE BILL 980 21
1 THE CHILD FEELS COMFORTABLE REPORTING COMPLAINTS AND FEELS SAFE
2 PENDING THE OUTCOME OF ANY INVESTIGATION.
3 (E) (1) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION, THE LOCAL
4 DEPARTMENT SHALL INCLUDE, IN DEVELOPMENTALLY APPROPRIATE LANGUAGE,
5 INFORMATION IN EACH CHILD’S RECORD ABOUT THE COMPLAINT PROCEDURE.
6 (2) THE INFORMATION SHALL INCLUDE:
7 (I) THE DEFINITION OF A COMPLAINT, INCLUDING EXAMPLES
8 OF SITUATIONS WHERE IT IS APPROPRIATE TO FILE A COMPLAINT;
9 (II) HOW TO FILE A FORMAL COMPLAINT WITH THE OFFICE;
10 (III) AN EXPLANATION OF THE PURPOSES OF THE OFFICE;
11 (IV) THE RESPONSE TIMES ESTABLISHED UNDER SUBSECTION
12 (C) OF THIS SECTION;
13 (V) POTENTIAL RESOLUTIONS BASED ON THE TYPE OF
14 COMPLAINTS;
15 (VI) HOW THE CHILD’S SAFETY WILL BE PROTECTED DURING
16 THE INVESTIGATION OF THE COMPLAINT;
17 (VII) AN EXPLANATION OF THE CHILD’S RIGHTS AS OUTLINED IN
18 ANY DEPARTMENT HANDBOOK FOR CHILDREN IN FOSTER CARE; AND
19 (VIII) ANY OTHER INFORMATION THE OFFICE REQUIRES.
20 (3) A CHILD SHALL BE GIVEN THE INFORMATION:
21 (I) AT THE CHILD’S INITIAL COURT HEARING;
22 (II) BEFORE ANY SUBSEQUENT COURT HEARINGS; AND
23 (III) BEFORE EVERY NEW PLACEMENT.
24 (F) THE OFFICE SHALL PROVIDE TRAINING ON COMPLAINT POLICIES AND
25 PROCEDURES TO ALL LOCAL DEPARTMENT CASEWORKERS, ATTORNEYS FOR
26 CHILDREN, OUT–OF–HOME PLACEMENT PROVIDERS, COURT–APPOINTED SPECIAL
27 ADVOCATES, JUDICIAL OFFICERS, AND OTHER PROFESSIONALS WORKING WITH
28 CHILDREN THROUGH THEIR CHILD IN NEED OF ASSISTANCE CASES AS PART OF

22 HOUSE BILL 980
1 THEIR EMPLOYMENT ORIENTATION AND CONTINUING PROFESSIONAL
2 DEVELOPMENT.
3 (G) (1) ON CONCLUSION OF AN INVESTIGATION UNDER THIS SECTION,
4 THE OFFICE SHALL INFORM THE CHILD, IN A DEVELOPMENTALLY APPROPRIATE
5 MANNER, OF THE OUTCOME OF THE INVESTIGATION.
6 (2) IF THE OUTCOME OF THE INVESTIGATION ENTAILS SITE VISITS
7 WITH THE CHILD FOR A SPECIFIED PERIOD OF TIME, THE CHILD SHALL BE
8 INFORMED OF THE SCOPE AND INTENT OF THIS FOLLOW–UP PROCESS.
9 (H) (1) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED UNDER PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS
10 SUBSECTION, THE OMBUDSMAN SHALL TREAT ALL COMPLAINTS RECEIVED UNDER
11 SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION AS CONFIDENTIAL, INCLUDING THE IDENTITIES
12 OF COMPLAINANTS AND INDIVIDUALS FROM WHOM INFORMATION IS ACQUIRED.
13 (2) THE OMBUDSMAN MAY DISCLOSE INFORMATION AS NECESSARY
14 TO ENABLE THE OMBUDSMAN TO PERFORM THE OMBUDSMAN’S DUTIES AND TO
15 SUPPORT ANY RECOMMENDATIONS RESULTING FROM AN INVESTIGATION.
16 (I) RECORDS RELATING TO COMPLAINTS RECEIVED BY THE OFFICE AND
17 THE INVESTIGATION OF COMPLAINTS ARE EXEMPT FROM DISCLOSURE UNDER THE
18 PUBLIC INFORMATION ACT.
19 6–5A–10.
20 (A) THE OFFICE SHALL REPORT IN A TIMELY MANNER TO THE SECRETARY
21 AND, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THIS ARTICLE, THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY:
22 (1) KNOWLEDGE OF ANY SYSTEMIC OR LIFE–THREATENING
23 PROBLEMS AND ANY FINDINGS, ACTIONS, AND RECOMMENDATIONS RELATING TO
24 INVESTIGATIONS REGARDING THE CARE, SUPERVISION, AND TREATMENT OF:
25 (I) CHILDREN AND FAMILIES WHO ARE AT RISK OF ABUSE OR
26 NEGLECT;
27 (II) CHILDREN IN DEPARTMENT OR LOCAL DEPARTMENT
28 CUSTODY; OR
29 (III) CHILDREN AND FAMILIES WHO RECEIVE CHILD
30 PROTECTIVE KINSHIP CARE OR FOSTER CARE SERVICES; AND

HOUSE BILL 980 23
1 (2) ALL OTHER FINDINGS, ACTIONS, AND RECOMMENDATIONS
2 RELATED TO THE ACTIVITIES REQUIRED UNDER THIS SUBTITLE.
3 (B) (1) THE OFFICE SHALL REPORT QUARTERLY TO THE SECRETARY.
4 (2) A COPY OF THE REPORT SHALL BE PROVIDED TO THE CITIZENS
5 REVIEW BOARD FOR CHILDREN, THE STATE COUNCIL ON CHILD ABUSE AND
6 NEGLECT, AND, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THIS ARTICLE, THE GENERAL
7 ASSEMBLY.
8 (3) THE REPORT SHALL INCLUDE:
9 (I) ALL ACTIVITIES OF THE OFFICE;
10 (II) ALL COMPLAINTS MADE TO THE OFFICE INCLUDING:
11 1. THE JURISDICTION WHERE THE INCIDENT
12 OCCURRED;
13 2. THE JURISDICTION THAT HAS CARE AND CUSTODY OF
14 THE CHILD IN NEED OF ASSISTANCE WHOSE CASE IS BEING REVIEWED;
15 3. THE NATURE OF THE COMPLAINT;
16 4. THE DISPOSITION OF THE COMPLAINT;
17 5. WHAT, IF ANY, FOLLOW–UP ACTION THE OFFICE TOOK
18 AND WHY;
19 6. THE CHILD’S PLACEMENT; AND
20 7. DEMOGRAPHIC INFORMATION ABOUT THE CHILD
21 INCLUDING AGE, GENDER IDENTITY, RACE, AND ETHNICITY;
22 (III) ACTIONS TAKEN BY THE DEPARTMENT OR A LOCAL
23 DEPARTMENT RESULTING FROM THE FINDINGS AND RECOMMENDATIONS OF THE
24 OFFICE, INCLUDING THE RESPONSE BY THE DEPARTMENT OR LOCAL DEPARTMENT;
25 AND
26 (IV) A SUMMARY OF ANY VIOLATIONS OF THE STANDARDS AND
27 REGULATIONS OF THE DEPARTMENT THAT REMAINED UNABATED FOR 30 DAYS OR
28 MORE DURING THE REPORTING PERIOD.

24 HOUSE BILL 980
1 (C) ON OR BEFORE NOVEMBER 30 EACH YEAR, BEGINNING IN 2028, THE
2 OFFICE SHALL REPORT TO THE SECRETARY, THE CITIZENS REVIEW BOARD FOR
3 CHILDREN, THE STATE COUNCIL ON CHILD ABUSE AND NEGLECT, THE GOVERNOR,
4 AND, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THIS ARTICLE, THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY
5 ON ALL THE ACTIVITIES OF THE OFFICE AND THE ACTIONS TAKEN BY THE
6 DEPARTMENT IN RESPONSE TO FINDINGS AND RECOMMENDATIONS OF THE OFFICE.
7 (D) BEFORE SUBMITTING A REPORT UNDER SUBSECTION (B) OR (C) OF THIS
8 SECTION, THE OFFICE SHALL REMOVE ANY IDENTIFYING INFORMATION AS
9 NECESSARY TO PROTECT THE PRIVACY OF THE CHILD AND THE CHILD’S FAMILY.
10 6–5A–11.
11 (A) A PERSON MAY NOT:
12 (1) DISCRIMINATE OR RETALIATE IN ANY MANNER AGAINST ANY
13 PERSON FOR:
14 (I) FILING A COMPLAINT UNDER THIS SUBTITLE; OR
15 (II) PROVIDING INFORMATION TO AN ADVOCATE OF A CHILD IN
16 GOOD FAITH; OR
17 (2) WILLFULLY INTERFERE WITH AN ADVOCATE OF A CHILD IN THE
18 PERFORMANCE OF THE ADVOCATE’S OFFICIAL DUTIES.
19 (B) A PERSON WHO VIOLATES SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION IS GUILTY
20 OF A MISDEMEANOR AND ON CONVICTION IS SUBJECT TO A FINE NOT EXCEEDING
21 $5,000 OR IMPRISONMENT NOT EXCEEDING 5 YEARS OR BOTH.
22 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
23 October 1, 2026 2027.
Approved:
